ce:section.ce:para:
The proposed formation mechanism of CDs is shown in Scheme 1
                        . The reaction temperature is one of the most important parameter affecting the rate of reaction and formation mechanism of carbon dots (see Table 1
                        ). The hydrothermal treatment of trans-aconitic acid and diethylenetriamine was conducted through reaction of precursors intermolecular dehydration upon heating which led to the formation of large-sized polymer like nanoparticles at a modest temperature (150 °C). These polymer nanoparticles condense as continuous intramolecular dehydration occurs due to heating process. At this step, C–C bonds are formed and crosslinked aromatic polymer clusters are shaped. As a result of further crosslinking and carbonization, nucleation initiates and subsequently carbogenic CDs are formed due to the progress of nucleation process and growth of carbon nuclei [15]. Zhu et al. suggested the same mechanism for fabrication of C-dots by hydrothermal treatment of citric acid and ethylenediamine [36].
